### Templates

Templates enable generic programming by allowing functions and classes to work with any data type without code duplication.

---

### Template Syntax

```cpp
template <typename T>
// Function or class definition using T
```

`typename` and `class` are interchangeable in template parameter declarations.

---

### Type and Non-Type Parameters

```cpp
template <typename T, int Size>  // Type + non-type parameter
class Array {
  T data[Size];
};

Array<int, 10> arr;
```

---

### Template Instantiation

When you use a template, the compiler generates a specific version for each type:

```cpp
template <typename T>
T max(T a, T b) { return (a > b) ? a : b; }

// Compiler generates:
// int max(int, int)
// double max(double, double)
// string max(string, string)
```

---

### Template Specialization

Provide a custom implementation for a specific type:

```cpp
template <>
const char* max<const char*>(const char* a, const char* b) {
  return (strcmp(a, b) > 0) ? a : b;
}
```

---

### Variadic Templates (C++11)

```cpp
template <typename... Args>
void printAll(Args... args) {
  (cout << ... << args) << endl;  // Fold expression (C++17)
}

printAll(1, 2.5, "hello", 'c');  // 12.5helloc
```

---

### Concepts (C++20)

```cpp
template <typename T>
concept Numeric = std::is_arithmetic_v<T>;

template <Numeric T>
T add(T a, T b) { return a + b; }
```

---

> **Key Point:** Templates are evaluated at compile time. Each unique type used with a template creates a separate instantiation. This enables zero-cost abstractions.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

template <typename T>
T maximum(T a, T b) {
  return (a > b) ? a : b;
}

int main() {
  cout << maximum(10, 20) << endl;        // int
  cout << maximum(3.14, 2.71) << endl;    // double
  cout << maximum("apple", "orange") << endl;  // string
  return 0;
}
